They want everyone to come and
drink beer and connect their

00:51:25.070 --> 00:51:27.280
networks and buy
cross connects.

00:51:27.280 --> 00:51:30.660
Telex, which also is in this
building, sometimes they say

00:51:30.660 --> 00:51:32.950
no, we're just selling space,
we'll do the cross connect for

00:51:32.950 --> 00:51:37.370
free, and that becomes a
kind of added value.

00:51:37.370 --> 00:51:39.110
Then there's the other layer.

00:51:39.110 --> 00:51:41.760
Ashburn's sort of a pure
example, because they own the

00:51:41.760 --> 00:51:44.720
dirt, they own the building,
it's all Equinix.

00:51:44.720 --> 00:51:46.730
This building is much more
complicated, because there is

00:51:46.730 --> 00:51:50.880
a legacy history of the
different telecom companies

00:51:50.880 --> 00:51:54.080
owning a suite of offices,
the different colocation

00:51:54.080 --> 00:51:54.630
companies--

00:51:54.630 --> 00:51:56.770
the kind of hotel equivalents,
like Equinix--

00:51:56.770 --> 00:52:01.640
owning another piece of the
building, and then whoever

00:52:01.640 --> 00:52:04.660
owns the building itself
allowing for the cables to run

00:52:04.660 --> 00:52:06.175
between floors or
between offices.

00:52:09.200 --> 00:52:13.520
At 60 Hudson, that code was
cracked first by Telex, sort

00:52:13.520 --> 00:52:16.070
of Equinix's major competitors,
because they sort

00:52:16.070 --> 00:52:18.980
of realized what the economic
value was--

00:52:18.980 --> 00:52:23.090
the union labor required to
connect two floors, the amount

00:52:23.090 --> 00:52:26.780
they had to charge one time or
two times or monthly, whatever

00:52:26.780 --> 00:52:29.000
it was, for that connection--

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.580
but essentially, to cut
out the local loop.

00:52:31.580 --> 00:52:36.650
To cut out the Bells or Verizon
or whoever it is where

00:52:36.650 --> 00:52:39.880
you are, and allow two networks
to connect directly--

00:52:39.880 --> 00:52:41.410
my router plugged into
your router.

00:52:46.920 --> 00:52:49.480
The ecosystem of
this building--

00:52:49.480 --> 00:52:54.060
and I'm on a little shaky ground
with this-- but the

00:52:54.060 --> 00:52:59.140
basics are that if a Deutsche
Telekom or a Cablevision comes

00:52:59.140 --> 00:53:01.710
in and has a suite of offices,
and the tradition has been

00:53:01.710 --> 00:53:03.860
that they then can connect from
their suite to someone

00:53:03.860 --> 00:53:05.630
else's suite, or if Equinix--

00:53:05.630 --> 00:53:07.750
I think has 30,000 square feet
of space in this building--

00:53:07.750 --> 00:53:10.620
can host a cage and everyone
can connect there.

00:53:10.620 --> 00:53:15.850
Or if you're building a large
global data network for a

00:53:15.850 --> 00:53:18.020
search engine, then the first
place you would go is to get a

00:53:18.020 --> 00:53:21.530
suite of offices here, so you
can connect to everybody else.

00:53:21.530 --> 00:53:29.850
To how the relationship is
between the landlord of this

00:53:29.850 --> 00:53:33.650
building, the sublandlord of
an Equinix or a Telex or a

00:53:33.650 --> 00:53:38.120
CoreSite, and then the existing
legacy communications

00:53:38.120 --> 00:53:41.800
companies that have beachheads
here, and who allows them to

00:53:41.800 --> 00:53:42.590
connect it--

00:53:42.590 --> 00:53:44.870
if they have only do the
construction at night or

00:53:44.870 --> 00:53:51.780
during the day and what the
limitations are on that--

00:53:51.780 --> 00:53:55.100
is still figuring it out.

00:53:55.100 --> 00:53:57.790
Certainly, if you're at Equinix,
and you're being told

00:53:57.790 --> 00:54:00.850
you can no longer grow because
we need the building for the

00:54:00.850 --> 00:54:05.850
office space, this is no
longer the most vibrant

00:54:05.850 --> 00:54:07.150
meeting place of networks.

00:54:07.150 --> 00:54:10.111
It becomes a very different
animal.

